# Git: Branch First

For any new PR-bound task, create a dedicated branch from the latest remote default branch before editing tracked files.

```bash
git fetch origin
git switch -c feature/<short-slug> origin/main
```

Always branch from `origin/main` (or `origin/master`), never from a stale local `main`. If the local default branch is needed, update it explicitly before branching:

```bash
git fetch origin
git switch main
git pull --ff-only origin main
git switch -c feature/<short-slug>
```

If `git pull --ff-only` fails because local `main` has diverged, do not silently branch from the stale state. Either:

- Branch directly from `origin/main` (`git switch -c <branch> origin/main`), or
- Reset local `main` to the remote with explicit user confirmation (`git reset --hard origin/main`), then branch.

Use `fix/<short-slug>` for fixes and `chore/<short-slug>` for maintenance.

If this repository uses `master`, replace `main` with `master` consistently in this rule and in `docs/agents/version-control.md`.

Do not commit directly on the default branch.
